# Suggestion: Useful AI Tools for the task

When **planning** a new task, feature, or workspace—or when the user asks for **tool recommendations** for things like research, RAG, semantic search, evaluation, vector databases, document extraction, or multi-agent workflows—suggest checking the project’s **Useful AI Tools** reference and surface one or two relevant options.

## Reference

**Full list:** [.cursor/lessons/08-useful-ai-tools-to-know-about.md](.cursor/lessons/08-useful-ai-tools-to-know-about.md)

## When to suggest

- User is planning a feature or project that involves: document search, RAG, embeddings, evaluation, vector DBs, multi-agent systems, or document parsing.
- User asks “what tool should I use for …” or “how do I …” in a way that maps to one of the tools (e.g. “improve my search results”, “evaluate my LLM”, “store embeddings”, “extract data from PDFs”).
- User is designing a workspace or pipeline and the task could benefit from a dedicated tool (e.g. Tesslate for doc hub, Braintrust for eval, OpenRouter for model switching).

## How to suggest

1. Briefly say that the project keeps a list of useful AI tools for exactly this kind of task.
2. Name 1–2 tools from the lesson that fit (with their “when to use it” in one short line).
3. Point to the lesson file so the user can read the full “what it is / why it’s useful / when to use it” and visit the links.

Example: “For measuring and improving LLM answers, the project’s Useful AI Tools list recommends **Braintrust** (evaluation platform for LLM outputs). For reordering search results by relevance, **Cohere Rerank** is listed. See [.cursor/lessons/08-useful-ai-tools-to-know-about.md](.cursor/lessons/08-useful-ai-tools-to-know-about.md) for the full list and links.”

Do not repeat the entire list; only surface tools that match the current task or question.
